        {
            "id": 1934127,
            "is_internal": false,
            "editable": false,
            "type": "Activities::BugInformative",
            "message": "Thanks for the report. Yes, we use SHA256 to hash the password before sending it over the wire. However, we only transmit the message over TLS, where we're rather sure that the connection is secure since we use HPKP, HSTS, and defend against rogue cert issuance with DNS CAA records, and CT notifications.\n\nSo, *if* someone was able to intercept and decrypt the login message, there could be a productive attack but we're reasonably sure that pinning our keys, using CAA records, and other mitigation factors are sufficient to block this kind of attack. In fact, I have written about this rather extensively [here](https://github.com/meteor/meteor-feature-requests/issues/44), where I tried to push for encryption and signing to mitigate this type of attack for folks running Meteor that don't have all of the HSTS/HPKP/CAA/CT stuff set up as we do.\n\nI'll be more than happy to reopen this if you can demonstrate a productive attack on app.legalrobot-uat.com.\nThanks!",
